s habits in a way that makes conscious one's everyday speech, comportment, countenance, and presence. The everyday body thus becomes an artwork, speaking in novel ways to the everyday self by revealing an alternative to the programmed ritual scripts through which most of us tend to survive. Reconsidering the Life of Power offers a compelling contemporary intercultural perspective on body, art, self, and society that bridges theory and practice by providing an actionable yet deeply philosophical approach to enhancing life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAesthetics, Chinese. 0aCritical theory--China. 0aPhilosophy, Chinese. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Confucianism. 4aPhilosophy : Aesthetics. 4aPhilosophy : Comparative Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848212540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438482125423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438482125/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles